In the compactified Bondi formalism, the vertices N, E, S, and W of the null parallelogram Σ cannot be chosen to lie exactly on the grid because, even in Minkowski space, the velocity of light in terms of a compactified radial coordinate x is not constant. As a consequence, the fields g, β, and V at the vertices of Σ are approximated to second order accuracy by interpolating between grid points. However, cancellations arise between these four interpolations so that Equation (8) is satisfied to fourth order accuracy. The net result is that the finite difference version of Equation (8) steps g radially outward one zone with an error of fourth order in grid size, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
